		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message31596201"><div class="spoiler"><input type="button" class="button" onClick="this.nextSibling.nextSibling.style.display='block';this.style.display='none';" value="Show spoiler"> <span class="spoiler_content" style="display:none"><input type="button" class="button" onClick="this.parentNode.style.display='none';this.parentNode.parentNode.childNodes[0].style.display='block';" value="Hide spoiler"><br>Durarara!! features a sprawling cast of eclectic personalities, supernatural intrigue, and cultural exploration of its chosen time period wrapped up in a slick and stylish package. Fortunately Durarara has its own unique identity not just with its modern setting but also a more methodically assembled plot.<br />
<br />
Durararas principle allure is appealingly presenting current day Ikebukuro and Japanese youth culture. interacting with their diverse collection of social contacts The series recognizes the important role that internet chat rooms, online associations, cell phones, and text messaging in teenagers social lives. Durarara integrates teen pop culture elements at all its seams without calling inappropriate attention to that aspect or stealing focus away from its main plot.<br />
<br />
The second great appeal of Durarara is its diverse and colorful mix of personalities. Through their adventures around Ikebukuro, we meet many colorful and instantly memorable characters However not all of the characters get as much attention as they might seem to all too often a new and exciting character would be introduced to great fanfare but makes there presence felt for only an episode or two before their out of the picture. the second half of the series shifts focus from telling the story from the perspective of the teen leads to being a story about them which is unfortunate since they are the least charismatic of the bunch. which is unfortunate for the real stars as they become background characters as the series progresses.<br />
<br />
The plotting is where the root of the problems lie It starts better than well enough after a first episode introducing the smattering of wild personalities it quickly sets into telling a number of parallel supernatural mysteries that initially appear oblique to each other but are intertwined. The early storylines build characters and situations that are more than they seem and layer genuinely surprising revelations and twists with misdirection all which constantly keeps the viewer guessing yet when expectations are heightened the series likes to pull back lower the tension and play off climaxes, theres a definite feeling of underutilized potential and unfinished business at the end.<br />
<br />
Durarara suits its colorful style and outlandish story best. the final set of episodes bogs down in teen angst that wasted the momentum the series had built up to that point. Overall though Durarara is still a great watch, hip, original, engaging, and vastly entertaining.<br />
<!--spoiler--></span></div></div><div class="postActions"></div><div class="sig">I know what you're thinking, punk. You're thinking "did he fire six shots or only five?" Now to tell you the truth I forgot myself in all this excitement. But being this is a .44 Magnum, the most powerful handgun in the world and will blow you head clean off, you've gotta ask yourself a question: "Do I feel lucky?" Well, do ya, punk?</div></td>
