		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message31659767">I'd like to elaborate a bit on the &quot;twists&quot; NavyCherub alluded to.<br />
<br />
<div class="spoiler"><input type="button" class="button" onClick="this.nextSibling.nextSibling.style.display='block';this.style.display='none';" value="Show spoiler"> <span class="spoiler_content" style="display:none"><input type="button" class="button" onClick="this.parentNode.style.display='none';this.parentNode.parentNode.childNodes[0].style.display='block';" value="Hide spoiler"><br>I recently watched the DVD special episodes for the first time, and I was reminded of what I loved about watching Durarara during its television broadcast.  It has this wonderful way of implying something amazing and terrifying and yet almost plausible without explicitly stating it.  All of the evidence is on the table, and you're left to draw one conclusion from it.  And then the show pulls back on the reigns, laughs, and slaps you in the back with a &quot;no way, man!  You didn't think we were actually going there, did you?&quot;<br />
<br />
Episode 12.5 (the first of the DVD special episodes) opens with a startling revelation.  A UFO sighted in Ikebukuro!  An invasion has begun!  What madness is this?  And with a voice over from the otaku gang, we discover that this is &quot;the day that fantasy became reality.&quot;  And then we backpedal a few hours, and in the 20 minutes of screentime that follow, we learn exactly how it came to be that these UFOs were sighted over Ikebukuro.  When we finally see how this happened (in a way that is still quite crazy, but perfectly in keeping with the constraints of the Durarara universe that has been established to this point), it is in many ways the fulfillment of a promise.  &quot;We'll show you exactly how this thing came to be.  But the answer may not be exactly what you expect.&quot;<br />
<br />
The main series executes this in a big way, by emitting a slow drip of information which gradually implies that Mika got decapitated and then had Celty's head surgically attached. Of course, the anime never actually tells us this.  It presents us with a series of facts, allows us to form our incorrect conclusion, and then laughs at us and gives us the real answer, the answer which fits the facts of the story and seems inevitable despite the fact that it is surprising.  I think that is the very definition of a &quot;twist&quot; executed well.<br />
<br />
Incidentally, this is something that Baccano played with a lot due to its anachronic nature.  (Durarara doesn't do it nearly as much due to being mostly chronological in nature, but it does get a few good punches in.)  One specific example from the Baccano discussion thread:<br />
<div class="spoiler"><input type="button" class="button" onClick="this.nextSibling.nextSibling.style.display='block';this.style.display='none';" value="Show spoiler"> <span class="spoiler_content" style="display:none"><input type="button" class="button" onClick="this.parentNode.style.display='none';this.parentNode.parentNode.childNodes[0].style.display='block';" value="Hide spoiler"><br><br />
<!--quote--><div class="quotetext"><strong>I said:</strong><!--quotesaid--><br>I think one of Baccano's greatest strengths is the way that it effectively uses non-linearity to play with assumptions and expectations.<br />
<br />
My favorite example of this is the scene in the train with Clair and one of the Russo gang members. Early on, we see Clair confront a Russo gang member in the rear car of the train and get held up at gunpoint. Later, Jacuzzi stumbles upon the aftermath of that confrontation, seeing a collapsed bloody body in a conductor's uniform that has sustained a gunshot wound to the head. The audience logically concludes from this that our friend Clair has met an untimely demise.<br />
<br />
It's not until episode 9 that we see the what really happened in between those two moments in time, and how the altercation between Clair and the gang member resulted in the bloody mess later discovered by Jacuzzi. The episode begins by showing us the same sequence of events we saw before: Clair confronts the gang member, and is held up at gunpoint. The audience braces for the moment we've all been waiting for, the moment when Clair is shot and becomes the bloody corpse that Jacuzzi stumbles upon. But this moment never comes. Clair is able to disarm his assailant and turn the tables on him, killing him with a gunshot to the head. And in that moment, we come to a real understanding of what Jacuzzi saw: it was the corpse of the Russo gang member that Clair killed. This is a complete subversion of our expectations: as it turns out, Clair is not the victim, but the killer.<br />
<br />
That sequence strikes me as bloody brilliant.<!--quote--></div><br />
<!--spoiler--></span></div><br />
<br />
After the revelation about Mika's head (haha of course Mika didn't get decapitated how could you possibly think otherwise), we're presented with several other twists.  Anri is Saika!  Kida is the leader of the Yellow Scarfs!  Mikado has his personal army!  And yet it's pretty uniformly agreed that the show goes south after we get into the habit of seeing every episode introduced by Rookiez is Punk'd (not that I have anything against the band).  I would contend that the reason that the twists in the latter half of the show don't work well is that they fail to properly deliver on the &quot;surprising yet inevitable&quot; factor that is required for a proper twist.  The show doesn't attempt to mislead you by implying answers that are different from the real reveal.  So when we get to the reveal, either you saw the writing on the wall and came to the correct conclusion about what the twist would be (in which case it doesn't feel surprising), or you missed the hints and got completely blindsided (in which case it doesn't feel inevitable).  The critical element that is missing here is <em>misdirection</em>.  In order to have a twist, you can't just have an information vacuum.  That's just a simple mystery.  There needs to be something that leads us along the wrong path and making us believe that we know what is coming while at the same time pointing toward a different real explanation that we smack ourselves for not having seen coming.<br />
<br />
Turning back to the Baccano example above, the reason the twist works is because it is a reversal of our expectations.  If the audience has <em>no</em> expectations, the &quot;twist&quot; doesn't work.  There needs to be incomplete information that allows the audience to form an incorrect picture of what happened, and <em>that</em> is the point at which the anime can deliver its big reveal.<!--spoiler--></span></div></div><div class="postActions"></div></td>
		</tr></table></div><div class="forum_boardrowspacer">&nbsp;</div>
